INSERT INTO `craft_content` (`id`, `elementId`, `locale`, `title`, `field_heading`, `field_body`, `field_client`, `field_dateDelivered`, `field_twitter`, `field_facebook`, `field_instagram`, `field_pinterest`, `field_github`, `field_lastFm`, `field_dribbble`, `field_tumblr`, `field_websiteLink`, `field_color`, `field_landingBody`, `field_readingSubtitle`, `field_readingAuthor`, `field_quoteAttribution`, `field_purchaseLink`, `dateCreated`, `dateUpdated`, `uid`) VALUES ('9', '9', 'en_us', 'Kick Republic', NULL, '<p>Kick Republic is a blog dedicated to the United States men\'s national soccer team. It\'s run by Tim Gray, an established writer with a love for the game. While the relevance of soccer has been growing here in the US, the enthusiasm for it online seems to have plateaued. And so Tim hopes to raise awareness for our team, which over the years has slowly become an actual international threat and a real joy to watch.</p><p>I worked with Tim from concept to completion as the sole designer and developer. In addition to the blog, Tim wanted to be able to put a focus on the players themselves, so we created profiles for each player. This allows us to give the site some extra depth. Visit a player\'s profile (like&nbsp;<a href=\"http://kickrepublic.com/players/clint-dempsey\">Clint Dempsey\'s</a>), and you\'ll see his primary position, current club, and a list of the articles on Kick Republic he\'s mentioned in.&nbsp;The site is developed in Craft, a beautiful and robust CMS that makes the player/post relationships easy to create, both for me, the developer, and for Tim, the writer. &nbsp;</p>', 'Tim Gray', '2013-09-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'http://kickrepublic.com', 'cf2e2c', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2014-03-28 02:41:19', '2014-05-23 15:20:27', '2b667cf2-c5a1-4a41-9132-bf186e5e770c');
INSERT INTO `craft_content` (`id`, `elementId`, `locale`, `title`, `field_heading`, `field_body`, `field_client`, `field_dateDelivered`, `field_twitter`, `field_facebook`, `field_instagram`, `field_pinterest`, `field_github`, `field_lastFm`, `field_dribbble`, `field_tumblr`, `field_websiteLink`, `field_color`, `field_landingBody`, `field_readingSubtitle`, `field_readingAuthor`, `field_quoteAttribution`, `field_purchaseLink`, `dateCreated`, `dateUpdated`, `uid`) VALUES ('10', '10', 'en_us', 'The Style of Utopias', NULL, '<p>It wasn\'t too long ago that us Westerners were all obsessed with the idea and promise of utopias. Life was going to be so grand. Beautiful and humanized machines were going to be perfectly functional. All of our daily chores would be taken care of push-button. New technologies in agriculture and logistics would solve world hunger. Advancements in psychology and sociology would give us such deep insights into the human condition that maybe, just maybe, we\'d all get along peacefully, happily, productively.</p><p>What the hell happened?</p><p>Had we been dreaming too big? </p><p>It appears we are destined to move through swinging periods of cultural giving and taking, of open-heartedness and selfishness. At some point towards the end of the 1960s we saw the rise of a certain generation aptly named the Me Generation, aka Baby Boomers. That\'s what happened. I\'m not here to blame any individuals for huge social failures, but rather to try to understand why it happened and what we might learn from it.</p><p>There was one particular movement which, in hindsight, seemed poised to make utopian dreams a reality. It was called the Human Potential Movement culminating in the 1960s of a lot great, big ideas from an impressive list of thinkers from the previous few decades. Let me go to the trouble of listing out just some of the people involved: Aldous Huxley, Viktor Frankl, Abraham Maslow, Alan Watts, Ansel Adams, Buckminster Fuller, Timonthy Leary, B.F. Skinner, Richard Feynman, Susan Sontag, Robert Anton Wilson, Joseph Campbell, Paul Tilich. The list is huge. And these are only the people I recognize and admire. </p><p>It eventually became the Self-Help industry, New Age spiritualism, and $100 yoga pants.</p><p>I don\'t know about you, but when I see someone shouting, \"Design can change the world!\", I\'m like Yeah, let\'s do it! I\'m full of hope and optimism and inspiration. But, really, I doubt we wield so much cultural power. Design can help carry the water, but it doesn\'t write the policy or command any armies. Even so, I do believe in the utility of design, in it\'s potentiality.</p><p>Piet Mondriaan saw art and design as a \"quasi-mysyical universal absolute.\" Made objects have spirits. All surfaces speak a meta-physical language. We might not think of it as such, but as designers we have our tenets and traditions and meditations and practices. It\'s awfully close to religion.</p><p>We used to live with utopian dreams. The first half of the twentieth century was boiling over with plans for technological transformations which would bring about all kinds of pleasures and make leisure possible in wonderful ways. One name for this was The Human Potential Movement, which promised that man was inching ever closer to an ideal, that all the despair and suffering of mankind might possibly be wiped out for good.</p><p>This movement died. As Berger writes, we \"lost the spiritual and political initiative for bringing about any transformation.\" </p><p>By the end of the 1960s we were moving into an era of the self, when ego and ideology overcame interest in society or globalized equality. The Me Generation, the Baby Boomers turned all their attention inward, egged on by ever-more-clever advertising (from a free-capitalism discovery that selfish people were far more susceptible to marketing propeganda, and successfully turned us all into dumb buying-machines).</p><p>My generation, and the Millennial generation following behind, have shown a willingness to push back against this selfishness. We are creating and adopting technologies which again  promise to transform our global world for the better, once again daring to believe in Utopias. We\'re still hesitant and cynical, but we are at least putting our toes in the water. We\'re building boats which might take us further from shore than we\'ve dared to go for decades. We\'re dreaming of better worlds again.</p><p>The 1970s through the mid 2000s was another era \"tragic and far less pure.\"</p><p>Berger says, \"Let me be quite clear. I am not suggesting that the de Stijl programme should have been more political.\" And in the same way our newfound attraction to utopias need not be political. In fact, must not be. If we again hope to progress towards a better world, we have to retain our cautiousness. If we don\'t, we might succeed only in establishing another \"movement\" doomed for inevitable failure. The best bet, then, is to not even name this new movement, to accept it exists only with the briefest of glances, to continue doing great things and attributing them to nothing in particular, to avoid at all costs writing any manifestos.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2014-03-28 12:29:24', '2014-05-23 15:20:28', '81da354d-5124-4ad7-b52d-5f397f1b01a9');
INSERT INTO `craft_content` (`id`, `elementId`, `locale`, `title`, `field_heading`, `field_body`, `field_client`, `field_dateDelivered`, `field_twitter`, `field_facebook`, `field_instagram`, `field_pinterest`, `field_github`, `field_lastFm`, `field_dribbble`, `field_tumblr`, `field_websiteLink`, `field_color`, `field_landingBody`, `field_readingSubtitle`, `field_readingAuthor`, `field_quoteAttribution`, `field_purchaseLink`, `dateCreated`, `dateUpdated`, `uid`) VALUES ('11', '12', 'en_us', 'An Evergreen Magazine', NULL, '<p>Nicole Jones\' wrote an article called&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.swellcontent.com/2013/02/editing-the-past/\">Editing the Past</a> last February, and I\'ve been thinking about it ever since. It\'s a strange little piece with nearly every sentence a question, but it has a persistent idea: Now that we have hundreds of posts over a span of years, what do we do with them?</p><p>I had already been asking myself a similar question. After blogging for a few years, I have a handful of posts I\'m really proud of. So what\'s the best way to present the writing? Nicole\'s barrage of questions broke free an idea for me, which is to create a page of evergreen content, structured like a magazine, that features all of my best articles.</p><p>This is finally a reality in brianfeeney.us v6.</p><p>I like the idea of a living magazine, something that can be updated when I\'ve learned something new, or if the world changes in a significant way. The Internet allows for an entirely different kind of evergreen content, content that might not be timeless from the start, but which could become so with a little pruning of the leaves. This kind of writing allows for spontaneity and immediacy, but frees me from the stigma of editing old blog posts.&nbsp;Mandy Brown has a version of this at&nbsp;<a href=\"http://aworkinglibrary.com\">A Working Library</a>, a&nbsp;really lovely site.</p><p>I\'m don\'t plan on having a \"blog\" again. I\'m happy with just a collection of articles. I\'ll tweet about newly posted writing when it happens, and I\'ll highlight old articles if I feel like it. But for now, look around and see if there\'s something you\'ve not yet seen.</p><p>This feels to me like a project other people could and should jump on board with. It\'s an open idea, similar&nbsp;to Fictive Kin\'s \"/Purpose\", which is wonderfully effective and complete. I would absolutely love to see an /Evergreen page from my favorite bloggers, like Frank Chimero, etc. But until they create one, here\'s mine.</p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2014-03-29 18:04:36', '2014-09-04 02:13:38', '9357960b-d4e9-4c7e-931c-76be46c2794f');
