INSERT INTO `craft_content` (`id`, `elementId`, `locale`, `title`, `field_heading`, `field_body`, `field_client`, `field_dateDelivered`, `field_twitter`, `field_facebook`, `field_instagram`, `field_pinterest`, `field_github`, `field_lastFm`, `field_dribbble`, `field_tumblr`, `field_websiteLink`, `field_color`, `field_landingBody`, `field_readingSubtitle`, `field_readingAuthor`, `field_quoteAttribution`, `field_purchaseLink`, `dateCreated`, `dateUpdated`, `uid`) VALUES ('688', '728', 'en_us', 'On Web Typography', NULL, '<p>An excellent introduction not only to typography for the web, but in how to properly use typography in general. From here on out, I\'ll suggest young designers read this short book as an introduction before the best of all typography books, <em>The Elements of Typography</em> by Robert Bringhurst.</p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', 'Jason Santa Maria', NULL, '', '2014-08-18 23:49:08', '2014-08-18 23:49:08', '9cc3d5a6-8bd2-4ba0-a5e9-b2d9a90fe103');
INSERT INTO `craft_content` (`id`, `elementId`, `locale`, `title`, `field_heading`, `field_body`, `field_client`, `field_dateDelivered`, `field_twitter`, `field_facebook`, `field_instagram`, `field_pinterest`, `field_github`, `field_lastFm`, `field_dribbble`, `field_tumblr`, `field_websiteLink`, `field_color`, `field_landingBody`, `field_readingSubtitle`, `field_readingAuthor`, `field_quoteAttribution`, `field_purchaseLink`, `dateCreated`, `dateUpdated`, `uid`) VALUES ('689', '729', 'en_us', 'Feeeds', NULL, '<p>A lot of people lately have been talking about RSS and the return of the blog. It seems as if everyone is wary of the end of Twitter, and are preparing themselves for a world without it. Most of us have already abandoned Facebook as a social hub, leaving it delegated as a second-class contact list. If we abandon Twitter, too, where are we going to go? There aren\'t any other promising social networks out there, and there doesn\'t appear to be one coming up any time soon. This leaves us looking back to the days pre-Social Media &mdash; back to blogs.</p><p>It\'s painfully easy to set up a blog today. You could use&nbsp;Tumblr, Squarespace, Blogspot, etc., and have a blog up in less than an hour. Most of these products require little to no knowledge of how the web works. It does&nbsp;take some initiative. It takes even more initiative to run your own blog on your own server on your own domain. These are the sites I\'m fascinated with. I love having my own website and I love that so many people I look up to have their own as well. I want to celebrate these people, raise them up, give them a higher platform. I want to connect them.</p><p>Are there any good indexes for all these popular blogs? I haven\'t found any. Why wouldn\'t there be? Is this something that should be built? I\'m seriously thinking about it. There may be a very good reason why such a thing doesn\'t exist. People smarter than me would know why. But I\'d love to build this thing.</p><p>I\'ve been calling my idea Feeeds (for lack of a better name).&nbsp;I think of it&nbsp;as non-social&nbsp;network. There would be personal accounts, but they don\'t exist for communication. Their sole&nbsp;purpose would be for building communities, while&nbsp;any and all conversation takes place elsewhere. You would come to Feeeds to see who\'s writing, but go to their own sites to see what they\'re saying.</p><p>I want to connect people with as little interference as possible. Which means that, for people who have their own websites and enjoy owning their own content, I wouldn\'t encroach upon what\'s theirs. There would be no&nbsp;walled garden. I believe in a wild, varied, decentralized Internet. Feeeds would be more like an address book, a place to go to find personal blogs to read and follow.</p><p>I want to stress again that I have no intention of building anything that purports to being the next new social network. I don\'t want the responsibility of owning anyone\'s content and I don\'t want anyone to feel like they\'re giving me anything. But I do want to build something that can help surface all the personal websites and blogs out there which deserve attention and love.</p><p>Brent Simmons names RSS as&nbsp;<a href=\"http://inessential.com/2014/08/27/waffle_on_social_media\">one of the pillars of the web that\'ll never go away</a>, and I believe that. I also believe we\'ve not fully tapped the power of RSS. There are billions of feeds out, many thousands of which are good blogs&nbsp;languishing in dark unlit corners. I want to take everyone\'s personal and beloved RSS feeds and show them the love they deserve.</p><p>Currently, the best avenue for exposing&nbsp;yourself to&nbsp;the greater world is Twitter. But Twitter is a poor Rolodex for personal websites. It\'s a terrible&nbsp;index. Even so,&nbsp;Twitter is where I go to find new people in my industry and to find out more about them. But might there be a better way? What if there *was* an actual index online for people with personal websites? There are so many great people out there maintaining their own websites. It\'s difficult to keep track of them all. And I\'d like to.</p><p>This isn\'t about marketing, either. The point of this wouldn\'t be for promoting oneself. It\'s merely a way to say, \"I\'m here.\" We can\'t rely on Google to be the hub&nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;its net is far too wide. Relying on nothing leaves the job to&nbsp;word of mouth.</p><p>So, again, why doesn\'t this exist? I suppose, most obviously, it requires buy-in. It needs to be voluntary. People would only engage with this if they chose to do so. Being voluntary, a certain threshold of users would be necessary before it became truly useful. This is so very hard to do, and failing at this has been the downfall of so many web services.</p><p>I have other ideas for this. It\'s a project that I can see growing and becoming something real.&nbsp;I\'d love to build it. Anyone care to help? Any and all thoughts about this are welcome.</p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2014-08-29 21:56:19', '2014-08-29 22:46:16', 'dac22b65-b482-4ec3-934f-fa9d9ea37d07');
INSERT INTO `craft_content` (`id`, `elementId`, `locale`, `title`, `field_heading`, `field_body`, `field_client`, `field_dateDelivered`, `field_twitter`, `field_facebook`, `field_instagram`, `field_pinterest`, `field_github`, `field_lastFm`, `field_dribbble`, `field_tumblr`, `field_websiteLink`, `field_color`, `field_landingBody`, `field_readingSubtitle`, `field_readingAuthor`, `field_quoteAttribution`, `field_purchaseLink`, `dateCreated`, `dateUpdated`, `uid`) VALUES ('690', '730', 'en_us', 'Museum Life', NULL, '<p>It\'s great working in a museum. At the Brooklyn Museum, the tech offices are on the sixth and top floor (inaccessible to the public). Anytime my eyes get that computer-screen-strain, I take a fifteen minute break, walk the stairs down a floor, and wander the galleries.</p><p>Art is refreshing. I’m really surprised I forgot that. There really isn’t anything like galleries full of paintings, sculpture, antique furniture. Images on the web are no substitute. When there is nothing artificial between the art and your eyes  the connection is physical, and you can feel it. If for no other reason, this is why art museums must exist.</p><p>The Brooklyn Museum isn’t a huge one. It’s sizable, but it’s footprint is maybe a quarter that of the Metropolitan Museum of Art, and our collection has a much quieter profile than MoMA. Still, there’s a lot of pride here, and our stated mission is wonderful: the goal of our institution is to be a museum for the local community, to be about the visitor, not our curators or any biennial nonsense.</p><p>I haven’t been able to talk about what I’m working on. I will soon, but we’re holding our collective tongues out of respect to our donor, who’s footing the bill for the whole thing, and is yet to make their own announcement. It’s an  exciting project, and its good natured and it’s attempting something really new. I am honored to be a part of it. </p><p>The museum is closed on Mondays and Tuesdays. Sometimes the lights are out and the galleries are dimly lit with only security lights. Walking around with museum like this makes the art somehow more alive, as if they’re sleeping. They have down time, too, just like us. It reminds me that we’re all lucky to have this art at our disposal. When the lights are on, they’re here for us. </p><p>What I’m working on might even bring people closer to this art. It could help them own it a little further, to get a little more out of their time visiting with us.  That’s the hope, anyway. I’ve learned to love art again, and I hope that this project might bring people closer to it, too.</p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2014-08-30 15:59:00', '2014-08-30 15:59:00', 'd84a1414-32db-48f3-bcfd-c859a006a635');
INSERT INTO `craft_content` (`id`, `elementId`, `locale`, `title`, `field_heading`, `field_body`, `field_client`, `field_dateDelivered`, `field_twitter`, `field_facebook`, `field_instagram`, `field_pinterest`, `field_github`, `field_lastFm`, `field_dribbble`, `field_tumblr`, `field_websiteLink`, `field_color`, `field_landingBody`, `field_readingSubtitle`, `field_readingAuthor`, `field_quoteAttribution`, `field_purchaseLink`, `dateCreated`, `dateUpdated`, `uid`) VALUES ('692', '732', 'en_us', 'No Longer Faving It', NULL, '<p>Twitter recently changed how their “fav” button works, which has completely broken its functionality for me. The old “fav” button used to be a beautifully simple way for me to communicate myself to someone. The new one, however, has an added, latent function: some “faved” tweets will be added to other users timelines, but in such a way that users have no control over. Even though the original function of the button hasn’t been removed, this added function feels distasteful to me and will keep me from clicking it. If I want someone else to see a tweet, I’ll retweet it.</p><p>I long ago cut down my use of Facebook’s Like button, too, also because of the unwanted, latent function built into it. “Liked” posts changes your feed, adding randomness and clutter, and is an invitation for brands to single you out for advertisements. No longer does clicking the Like button mean “I like this”, but it also means “I like these kinds of things and want to see more of them and brand-related items for sale”. No thank you.</p><p>These are two fascinating examples of how design choices can unintentionally break a feature. Neither Twitter nor Facebook set out to break their Like and Fav buttons. They were only attempting to add functionality, which, admittedly, are practically invisible and will never be noticed by most users. Regardless of its visibility, the additional baggage adds weight and cruft to the feature for those who know it’s there. It becomes a discouragement.</p><p>It seems to me the Twitter change is worse, for two reasons. The clicking of a Facebook Like button is detrimental to me and my personal feed, whereas clicking the new Fav button is detrimental to other users feeds. But also kind of detrimental to me because if they see my name attached to a tweet in their feed they didn’t ask for, that potentially works against my reputation: I’m the idiot who plopped down that unasked-for tweet.</p><p>And second, it means I can no longer use Fav button as I used to, knowing now that it also means a very different thing. Twitter has effectively poisoned a wonderful communication channel on their service. This hurts Twitter, and it hampers my use of the service.</p><p>It must be incredibly hard to design for products that have the scale of Twitter and Facebook, so I don’t begrudge the men and women who worked on these changes. But I do take it as a lesson in how to avoid breaking what works. </p><p>So now, as a Twitter power user, I need to be aware of the consequences of my actions. Faving a tweet means maybe stepping on the toes of my followers. This is bad for all parties involved.</p><p>I can still use it, of course, but now it’s like a Russian roulette fart into someone else’s Twitter feed. I don’t want that. No one wants that.</p><p>Compare this with how Facebook “Like” buttons operate behind the scenes and you can see the pattern.</p><p>I avoided “liking” posts on Facebook because I didn’t want my feed polluted with suggested junk, and now I will avoid “faving” any posts on twitter to help keep my followers feeds free from junk. </p><p>These are two fascinating examples of how design choices can unintentionally break a feature. </p><p>If I’m no longer “faving” tweets, I’m sure I’m not the only one. In fact, most of the people who Fav my tweets are what I would consider power users. It wouldn’t surprise me if I stopped receiving favs altogether.</p><p>Brian Feeney</p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2014-08-30 16:01:36', '2014-08-30 16:03:15', 'e1169f81-3a7a-4e9b-b666-ec79d3ba3dbf');
