INSERT INTO `craft_entrydrafts` (`id`, `entryId`, `sectionId`, `creatorId`, `locale`, `name`, `notes`, `data`, `dateCreated`, `dateUpdated`, `uid`) VALUES ('1', '16', '2', '1', 'en_us', 'Draft 1', NULL, '{\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"BrianFeeney.us Version 6 of ?\",\"slug\":\"brianfeeny.us-version-6-of\",\"postDate\":1396130580,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":0,\"fields\":{\"2\":\"<p>As of March, 2014, this website has gone through six separate designs. That\'s six in only three years. I have a designer\'s disease: incurable dissatisfaction. It\'s impossible for me to stop imaging what I could do better, build tougher, design more affectively, attractively. It doesn\'t stop. And it shouldn\'t stop.&nbsp;<\\/p><p>I would love it if I could be happy with a design for more than six months.&nbsp;<\\/p><p>Oddly enough, the itch to redesign always happens when I\'m at my busiest.<\\/p>\",\"28\":\"\",\"25\":\"\"}}', '2014-03-30 21:30:46', '2014-06-04 12:48:56', 'b8a2413d-459d-466f-84c2-adee6a98bec6');
INSERT INTO `craft_entrydrafts` (`id`, `entryId`, `sectionId`, `creatorId`, `locale`, `name`, `notes`, `data`, `dateCreated`, `dateUpdated`, `uid`) VALUES ('4', '732', '2', '1', 'en_us', 'Draft 1', NULL, '{\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"No Longer Faving It\",\"slug\":\"no-longer-faving-it-1\",\"postDate\":null,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":0,\"fields\":{\"2\":\"<p>Twitter recently changed how their \\u201cfav\\u201d button works, which has completely broken its functionality for me. The old \\u201cfav\\u201d button used to be a beautifully simple way for me to communicate myself to someone. The new one, however, has an added, latent function: some \\u201cfaved\\u201d tweets will be added to other users timelines, but in such a way that users have no control over. Even though the original function of the button hasn\\u2019t been removed, this added function feels distasteful to me and will keep me from clicking it. If I want someone else to see a tweet, I\\u2019ll retweet it.<\\/p><p>I long ago cut down my use of Facebook\\u2019s Like button, too, also because of the unwanted, latent function built into it. \\u201cLiked\\u201d posts changes your feed, adding randomness and clutter, and is an invitation for brands to single you out for advertisements. No longer does clicking the Like button mean \\u201cI like this\\u201d, but it also means \\u201cI like these kinds of things and want to see more of them and brand-related items for sale\\u201d. No thank you.<\\/p><p>These are two fascinating examples of how design choices can unintentionally break a feature. Neither Twitter nor Facebook set out to break their Like and Fav buttons. They were only attempting to add functionality, which, admittedly, are practically invisible and will never be noticed by most users. Regardless of its visibility, the additional baggage adds weight and cruft to the feature for those who know it\\u2019s there. It becomes a discouragement.<\\/p><p>It seems to me the Twitter change is worse, for two reasons. The clicking of a Facebook Like button is detrimental to me and my personal feed, whereas clicking the new Fav button is detrimental to other users feeds. But also kind of detrimental to me because if they see my name attached to a tweet in their feed they didn\\u2019t ask for, that potentially works against my reputation: I\\u2019m the idiot who plopped down that unasked-for tweet.<\\/p><p>And second, it means I can no longer use Fav button as I used to, knowing now that it also means a very different thing. Twitter has effectively poisoned a wonderful communication channel on their service. This hurts Twitter, and it hampers my use of the service.<\\/p><p>It must be incredibly hard to design for products that have the scale of Twitter and Facebook, so I don\\u2019t begrudge the men and women who worked on these changes. But I do take it as a lesson in how to avoid breaking what works. <\\/p><p>So now, as a Twitter power user, I need to be aware of the consequences of my actions. Faving a tweet means maybe stepping on the toes of my followers. This is bad for all parties involved.<\\/p><p>I can still use it, of course, but now it\\u2019s like a Russian roulette fart into someone else\\u2019s Twitter feed. I don\\u2019t want that. No one wants that.<\\/p><p>Compare this with how Facebook \\u201cLike\\u201d buttons operate behind the scenes and you can see the pattern.<\\/p><p>I avoided \\u201cliking\\u201d posts on Facebook because I didn\\u2019t want my feed polluted with suggested junk, and now I will avoid \\u201cfaving\\u201d any posts on twitter to help keep my followers feeds free from junk. <\\/p><p>These are two fascinating examples of how design choices can unintentionally break a feature. <\\/p><p>If I\\u2019m no longer \\u201cfaving\\u201d tweets, I\\u2019m sure I\\u2019m not the only one. In fact, most of the people who Fav my tweets are what I would consider power users. It wouldn\\u2019t surprise me if I stopped receiving favs altogether.<\\/p><p>Brian Feeney<\\/p>\",\"28\":\"\"}}', '2014-08-30 16:01:36', '2014-08-30 16:01:36', 'dcc2fbe1-b9d6-4cec-8a31-3f3dcd385eb6');
