INSERT INTO `craft_entryversions` (`id`, `entryId`, `sectionId`, `creatorId`, `locale`, `num`, `notes`, `data`, `dateCreated`, `dateUpdated`, `uid`) VALUES ('40', '278', '2', '1', 'en_us', '6', NULL, '{\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Christ in the Desert\",\"slug\":\"christ-in-the-desert\",\"postDate\":1396404540,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"2\":\"<p><img src=\\\"{asset:280:url}\\\" style=\\\"font-family: Arial, Helvetica, Verdana, Tahoma, sans-serif; font-size: 15px;\\\"><\\/p><p>There are thousands of Jesuses. He\'s a plural figure.<\\/p><p>A painting came to mind, the only painting of Jesus Matthew had ever admired, the only one which seemed to capture the Real Man and not the cartoonish Saturday- morning kids TV super-friend of a Jesus that gets passed around from pew to pew, congregant to congregant, even among the adults, a painting by Ivan Kramskoi called Christ in the Wilderness. A Russian realist painting, it displayed a seated Jesus, hands clasped, glaring downwards at about a 35\\u00b0 angle with dark recessed eyes and a pale malnourished countenance which bespoke inner turmoil and cloudy moralization, dirty hair, dirty feet, and wearing a robe more peasant-like than king-like. This Jesus, Kramskoi\'s Jesus, seemed to Matthew to be the Real Jesus, a man, a prophet, but not necessarily the son of God he was purported to be, not a Jesus you prayed to, but a Jesus you might sit beside at a bar and kvetch over beers. Kramskoi\'s Jesus was a lost Jesus, the wandering Jesus, homeless and searching, a Jesus that questioned his own motives and, most likely, his own sanity. This was the Jesus who had roamed Galilee and Judea two- thousand years ago as a prophet, a philosopher, a man among men.<\\/p><p>Yet Kramskoi\'s Jesus was not Matthew\'s visitor C. They were two different Jesuses. And, the more Matthew thought about it, the more Jesuses there seemed to be. A Jesus for Catholics, a Jesus for Protestants, a Jesus for the Jews, a Jesus for the Mormons, a Jesus for the Muhammadians, a Jesus for leather-clad bikers, a Jesus for scarf-knitting grandmothers, a Jesus for door-knocking Evangelicals, a Jesus for historians, a Jesus for bhodisattvas, a Jesus for Christian military camp attendees, a Jesus for ex- and current American presidents. Where did it end? And were they not all the same man, could they be the same man? Not possible.<\\/p>\",\"28\":\"\",\"25\":[]}}', '2014-04-02 02:35:38', '2014-06-04 12:48:57', '7eb492aa-ee3a-4240-8ccb-257dd22f8738');
