INSERT INTO `craft_entryversions` (`id`, `entryId`, `sectionId`, `creatorId`, `locale`, `num`, `notes`, `data`, `dateCreated`, `dateUpdated`, `uid`) VALUES ('46', '278', '2', '1', 'en_us', '10', NULL, '{\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Christ in the Desert\",\"slug\":\"christ-in-the-desert\",\"postDate\":1396404540,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"2\":\"<p><img src=\\\"{asset:280:url}\\\"><\\/p><p>There are thousands of Jesuses. He\'s a plural figure.<\\/p><p>A painting came to mind, the only painting of Jesus Matthew had ever admired, the only one which seemed to capture the Real Man and not the cartoonish Saturday- morning kids TV super-friend of a Jesus that gets passed around from pew to pew, congregant to congregant, even among the adults, a painting by Ivan Kramskoi called Christ in the Wilderness. A Russian realist painting, it displayed a seated Jesus, hands clasped, glaring downwards at about a 35\\u00b0 angle with dark recessed eyes and a pale malnourished countenance which bespoke inner turmoil and cloudy moralization, dirty hair, dirty feet, and wearing a robe more peasant-like than king-like. This Jesus, Kramskoi\'s Jesus, seemed to Matthew to be the Real Jesus, a man, a prophet, but not necessarily the son of God he was purported to be, not a Jesus you prayed to, but a Jesus you might sit beside at a bar and kvetch over beers. Kramskoi\'s Jesus was a lost Jesus, the wandering Jesus, homeless and searching, a Jesus that questioned his own motives and, most likely, his own sanity. This was the Jesus who had roamed Galilee and Judea two- thousand years ago as a prophet, a philosopher, a man among men.<\\/p><p>Yet Kramskoi\'s Jesus was not Matthew\'s visitor C. They were two different Jesuses. And, the more Matthew thought about it, the more Jesuses there seemed to be. A Jesus for Catholics, a Jesus for Protestants, a Jesus for the Jews, a Jesus for the Mormons, a Jesus for the Muhammadians, a Jesus for leather-clad bikers, a Jesus for scarf-knitting grandmothers, a Jesus for door-knocking Evangelicals, a Jesus for historians, a Jesus for bhodisattvas, a Jesus for Christian military camp attendees, a Jesus for ex- and current American presidents. Where did it end? And were they not all the same man, could they be the same man? Not possible.<\\/p>\",\"28\":\"\",\"25\":[]}}', '2014-04-02 12:42:41', '2014-06-04 12:48:57', 'ac0eb943-f1fc-4b3b-8bb5-31b7a6ee55b7');
INSERT INTO `craft_entryversions` (`id`, `entryId`, `sectionId`, `creatorId`, `locale`, `num`, `notes`, `data`, `dateCreated`, `dateUpdated`, `uid`) VALUES ('47', '12', '2', '1', 'en_us', '4', NULL, '{\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"An Evergreen Magazine\",\"slug\":\"introduction-to-the-first-edition\",\"postDate\":1396116240,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"2\":\"<p>Nicole Jones\' wrote an article called&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.swellcontent.com\\/2013\\/02\\/editing-the-past\\/\\\">Editing the Past<\\/a> last February, and I\'ve been thinking about it ever since. It\'s a strange little piece with nearly every sentence a question, but it has a persistent idea: Now that we have hundreds of posts over a span of years, what do we do with them?<\\/p><p>I had already been asking myself a similar question. After blogging for a few years, I have a handful of posts I\'m really proud of, so what\'s the best way to present the writing? But her barrage of questions broke free an idea for me, which is to create a page of evergreen content, structured like a magazine, that features all of my best articles.<\\/p><p>This is finally a reality in brianfeeney.us v6.<\\/p><p>I like the idea of a living magazine, something that can be updated when I\'ve learned something new, or if the world changes in a significant way. The Internet allows for an entirely different kind of evergreen content, content that isn\'t necessarily timeless from the start, but that can become so with a little pruning of the leaves. This kind of writing still allows for spontaneity and immediacy, but frees me from the stigma of editing old blog posts.&nbsp;Mandy Brown has a version of this at&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/aworkinglibrary.com\\\">A Working Library<\\/a>, a&nbsp;really lovely site.<\\/p><p>I\'ve long wondered why musical artists never re-record their old songs. Will Oldham has done it and I think it works. There\'s certainly no hard-lined reason not to. I suppose releasing live recordings can be a version of this, but it doesn\'t carry the same weight. Fresh takes on old ideas can be as surprising and enlightening as new ones. It seems a shame to let all these great things sit on shelves, gathering dust, showing their age. <\\/p><p>I\'m re-designing this blog (again) and in this round I\'ll be including a section called Evergreen. It even feels to me like a similar project to Fictive Kin\'s \\/Purpose idea, which is wonderfully effective and complete. Evergreen will be arranged something like a magazine, with a letter from the editor (me) and everything. Sections for design and culture wrting, music reviews, photos, personal essays. I would absolutely love to see an \\/Evergreen page from my favorite bloggers, like Frank Chimero, Koi Vinh, Matt Gemmell, etc.<\\/p>\"}}', '2014-04-03 23:22:03', '2014-06-04 12:48:57', 'd233f4e1-bba8-4a3e-81ad-0d73799c3848');
