INSERT INTO `craft_entryversions` (`id`, `entryId`, `sectionId`, `creatorId`, `locale`, `num`, `notes`, `data`, `dateCreated`, `dateUpdated`, `uid`) VALUES ('69', '10', '2', '1', 'en_us', '2', NULL, '{\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"The Style of Utopias\",\"slug\":\"the-human-potential-movement\",\"postDate\":1396009740,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"2\":\"<p>It wasn\'t too long ago that us Westerners were all obsessed with the idea and promise of utopias. Life was going to be so grand. Beautiful and humanized machines were going to be perfectly functional. All of our daily chores would be taken care of push-button. New technologies in agriculture and logistics would solve world hunger. Advancements in psychology and sociology would give us such deep insights into the human condition that maybe, just maybe, we\'d all get along peacefully, happily, productively.<\\/p><p>What the hell happened?<\\/p><p>Had we been dreaming too big? <\\/p><p>It appears we are destined to move through swinging periods of cultural giving and taking, of open-heartedness and selfishness. At some point towards the end of the 1960s we saw the rise of a certain generation aptly named the Me Generation, aka Baby Boomers. That\'s what happened. I\'m not here to blame any individuals for huge social failures, but rather to try to understand why it happened and what we might learn from it.<\\/p><p>There was one particular movement which, in hindsight, seemed poised to make utopian dreams a reality. It was called the Human Potential Movement culminating in the 1960s of a lot great, big ideas from an impressive list of thinkers from the previous few decades. Let me go to the trouble of listing out just some of the people involved: Aldous Huxley, Viktor Frankl, Abraham Maslow, Alan Watts, Ansel Adams, Buckminster Fuller, Timonthy Leary, B.F. Skinner, Richard Feynman, Susan Sontag, Robert Anton Wilson, Joseph Campbell, Paul Tilich. The list is huge. And these are only the people I recognize and admire. <\\/p><p>It eventually became the Self-Help industry, New Age spiritualism, and $100 yoga pants.<\\/p><p>I don\'t know about you, but when I see someone shouting, \\\"Design can change the world!\\\", I\'m like Yeah, let\'s do it! I\'m full of hope and optimism and inspiration. But, really, I doubt we wield so much cultural power. Design can help carry the water, but it doesn\'t write the policy or command any armies. Even so, I do believe in the utility of design, in it\'s potentiality.<\\/p><p>Piet Mondriaan saw art and design as a \\\"quasi-mysyical universal absolute.\\\" Made objects have spirits. All surfaces speak a meta-physical language. We might not think of it as such, but as designers we have our tenets and traditions and meditations and practices. It\'s awfully close to religion.<\\/p><p>We used to live with utopian dreams. The first half of the twentieth century was boiling over with plans for technological transformations which would bring about all kinds of pleasures and make leisure possible in wonderful ways. One name for this was The Human Potential Movement, which promised that man was inching ever closer to an ideal, that all the despair and suffering of mankind might possibly be wiped out for good.<\\/p><p>This movement died. As Berger writes, we \\\"lost the spiritual and political initiative for bringing about any transformation.\\\" <\\/p><p>By the end of the 1960s we were moving into an era of the self, when ego and ideology overcame interest in society or globalized equality. The Me Generation, the Baby Boomers turned all their attention inward, egged on by ever-more-clever advertising (from a free-capitalism discovery that selfish people were far more susceptible to marketing propeganda, and successfully turned us all into dumb buying-machines).<\\/p><p>My generation, and the Millennial generation following behind, have shown a willingness to push back against this selfishness. We are creating and adopting technologies which again  promise to transform our global world for the better, once again daring to believe in Utopias. We\'re still hesitant and cynical, but we are at least putting our toes in the water. We\'re building boats which might take us further from shore than we\'ve dared to go for decades. We\'re dreaming of better worlds again.<\\/p><p>The 1970s through the mid 2000s was another era \\\"tragic and far less pure.\\\"<\\/p><p>Berger says, \\\"Let me be quite clear. I am not suggesting that the de Stijl programme should have been more political.\\\" And in the same way our newfound attraction to utopias need not be political. In fact, must not be. If we again hope to progress towards a better world, we have to retain our cautiousness. If we don\'t, we might succeed only in establishing another \\\"movement\\\" doomed for inevitable failure. The best bet, then, is to not even name this new movement, to accept it exists only with the briefest of glances, to continue doing great things and attributing them to nothing in particular, to avoid at all costs writing any manifestos.&nbsp;<\\/p>\",\"28\":[\"315\"],\"25\":[{\"id\":\"11\",\"enabled\":1,\"archived\":\"0\",\"locale\":\"en_us\",\"uri\":null,\"dateCreated\":\"2014-03-28 12:29:24\",\"dateUpdated\":\"2014-03-28 12:29:24\",\"fieldId\":\"25\",\"ownerId\":\"10\",\"typeId\":\"4\",\"sortOrder\":1}]}}', '2014-04-16 13:20:12', '2014-06-04 12:48:57', '6d979452-0afa-4a1b-b9ff-687db8e63c96');
