INSERT INTO `craft_entryversions` (`id`, `entryId`, `sectionId`, `creatorId`, `locale`, `num`, `notes`, `data`, `dateCreated`, `dateUpdated`, `uid`) VALUES ('349', '729', '2', '1', 'en_us', '1', '', '{\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Feeeds\",\"slug\":\"feeeds\",\"postDate\":1409349379,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"2\":\"<p>A lot of people lately have been talking about RSS and the return of the blog. It seems as if everyone is wary of the end of Twitter, and are preparing themselves for a world without it. Most of us have already abandoned Facebook as a social hub, leaving it delegated as a second-class contact list. If we abandon Twitter, too, where are we going to go? There aren\'t any other promising social networks out there, and there doesn\'t appear to be one coming up any time soon. This leaves us looking back to the days pre-Social Media &mdash; back to blogs.<\\/p><p><br>It\'s painfully easy to set up a blog today. You have at your disposal Tumblr, Squarespace, Blogspot, etc. Most of these products require little to no knowledge of how the web works. Still, it takes some initiative. It takes even more initiative to run your own blog on your own server on your own domain. These are the sites I\'m fascinated with. I love having my own website and I love that so many people I look up to have their own as well. I want to celebrate these people, raise them up, give them a higher platform. I want to connect them.<br><br>I want to connect people with as little interference as possible. Which means that, for people who have their own websites and enjoy owning their own content, I don\'t want to encroach upon what\'s theirs. I want to help them promote their online presence without requiring anything to live inside a walled garden. I believe in a wild, varied, decentralized Internet. I would do this with RSS.<br><br>Brent Simmons names RSS as&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/inessential.com\\/2014\\/08\\/27\\/waffle_on_social_media\\\">one of the pillars of the web that\'ll never go away<\\/a>, and I believe that. I also believe we\'ve not fully tapped the power of RSS. There are billions of feeds out, many thousands of which are good blogs&nbsp;languishing in dark unlit corners. I want to take everyone\'s personal and beloved RSS feeds and show them the love they deserve.<br><br>Is this not possible?<br><br>Currently, the best avenue for sharing yourself with the greater world is Twitter. But Twitter is a poor Rolodex for personal websites. It doesn\'t really pretend to be an index of any kind. Twitter is where I go to find new people in my industry and to find out more about them. But might there be a better way? What if there *was* an actual index online for people with personal websites? There are so many great people out there maintaining their own websites.. It\'s difficult to keep track of them all. And I\'d like to.<br><br>I want to stress again that I have no intention of building anything that purports to being the next new social network. I don\'t really want to build a social network at all. I don\'t want the responsibility of owning anyone\'s content and I don\'t want anyone to feel like they\'re giving me anything. But I do want to build something that can help surface all the personal websites and blogs out there which deserve attention and love.<br><br>I want to make the Interstate highways for personal blogs.<br><br>I think it\'s fair to separate internet users into two camps: those that *make* Internet, and those that merely use it.<br><br>I think of Feeeds as an anti-social network. There would be personal accounts, but they don\'t exist for communication. Their purpose would be for building communities. Any and all conversation takes place elsewhere. You would come to Feeeds to see who\'s writing, but you would go to their own sites to see what they\'re saying.<br><br>This isn\'t about marketing, either. The point of this wouldn\'t be for promoting oneself. It\'s merely a way to say, \\\"I\'m here.\\\" We can\'t rely on Google to be the hub. Its net is far too wide. Relying on nothing means it\'s back to word of mouth.<br><br>Why doesn\'t this exist? Most obviously, it requires buy-in. I wouldn\'t consider doing this if it weren\'t voluntary. People would only engage with this if they chose to do so. Being voluntary, a certain threshold of users would be necessary before it became truly useful.<br><br>Creating the connective tissue is one part, but if the site were merely that it would be a little thin. Perhaps the solution would be for the site to include its own RSS reader. Using that RSS reader would also be voluntary, but it would provide a center. All the feeds of people you follow would be included. It would be something like Twitter for blog posts, which is really an inversion of an inversion, as twitter itself is basically an RSS reader of 140char blog posts. Feeeds brings it back to what might have happened had blogs evolved in a Facebook\\/Twitter-less universe.<br><br>When Google Reader died, there was going to be a big resurgence in feed readers, but that didn\'t really happen. A few new readers popped up, and another couple beefed up their quality, but that\'s about it. I haven\'t noticed any innovation.<br><br>I\'d love to be the one to build this. Anyone care to help? Any and all thoughts about this are welcome.<\\/p>\",\"28\":\"\"}}', '2014-08-29 21:56:20', '2014-08-29 21:56:20', '626f1e61-3851-4efc-8f1c-745f7c0ecc82');
