INSERT INTO `craft_searchindex` (`elementId`, `attribute`, `fieldId`, `locale`, `keywords`) VALUES ('35', 'field', '2', 'en_us', ' religion dispatches has an article up introducing david barton a politically connected and motivated amateur historian whose career ambition is to make our children dumber he is a historical revisionist working against well established facts and two hundred years worth of academic peer reviewed study desperately trying to alter how we view the past barton s intent is not to produce scholarship but to influence public policy he simply is playing a different game than worrying about scholarly credibility his protestations to the contrary notwithstanding his game is to inundate public policy makers including local and state education boards as well as congress with ideas packaged as products that will move policy it is history not as it happened but how someone might wish it had happened this is fictional thinking that has it s place in film and literature not at school board meetings and congressional hearings while barton s intentions are underhanded and sinister a playful strain of historical revisionism has been running through recent design history a great example of how paradigmatic concepts grow out of entirely different disciplines look at olly moss s redesigned posters for star wars iv v and vi and these wu tang album covers re imagined as blue note designs by logan walters this is a type of revisionist history is it not the idea is the same to change what exists in order to present a more favorable view to a particular person or group of my previous examples one is corrosive to community the other makes bloggers giggle but the idea is the same i mean to focus on the concept not the cultural impact of this creative way of thinking the philosopher karl popper wrote that each generation has its own troubles and problems and therefore its own interests and its own point of view we live in a time where history seems to be breaking down where irony and post modern thought has become a snake eating its own tail i think the catalyst for historical revisionism in either politics or design comes from an overabundance of educated people and lack of big questions left to answer all of this excess energy and enthusiasm turns into a playful tinkering of facts what if this what if that part of it comes from boredom we ve seen those original star wars posters enough already what would they look like if they were designed today we know our founding fathers were protestants and deists what if they were actually 21st century evangelicals i do not mean to downplay the danger of what barton is doing but i do mean to make light of it inspiration can come from anywhere even fictional worlds in the immortal words of eli cash everyone knows custer died at little bighorn what this book presupposes is maybe he didn t ');
