INSERT INTO `craft_searchindex` (`elementId`, `attribute`, `fieldId`, `locale`, `keywords`) VALUES ('732', 'field', '2', 'en_us', ' twitter recently changed how their fav button works which has completely broken its functionality for me the old fav button used to be a beautifully simple way for me to communicate myself to someone the new one however has an added latent function some faved tweets will be added to other users timelines but in such a way that users have no control over even though the original function of the button hasn t been removed this added function feels distasteful to me and will keep me from clicking it if i want someone else to see a tweet i ll retweet it i long ago cut down my use of facebook s like button too also because of the unwanted latent function built into it liked posts changes your feed adding randomness and clutter and is an invitation for brands to single you out for advertisements no longer does clicking the like button mean i like this but it also means i like these kinds of things and want to see more of them and brand related items for sale no thank you these are two fascinating examples of how design choices can unintentionally break a feature neither twitter nor facebook set out to break their like and fav buttons they were only attempting to add functionality which admittedly are practically invisible and will never be noticed by most users regardless of its visibility the additional baggage adds weight and cruft to the feature for those who know it s there it becomes a discouragement it seems to me the twitter change is worse for two reasons the clicking of a facebook like button is detrimental to me and my personal feed whereas clicking the new fav button is detrimental to other users feeds but also kind of detrimental to me because if they see my name attached to a tweet in their feed they didn t ask for that potentially works against my reputation i m the idiot who plopped down that unasked for tweet and second it means i can no longer use fav button as i used to knowing now that it also means a very different thing twitter has effectively poisoned a wonderful communication channel on their service this hurts twitter and it hampers my use of the service it must be incredibly hard to design for products that have the scale of twitter and facebook so i don t begrudge the men and women who worked on these changes but i do take it as a lesson in how to avoid breaking what works so now as a twitter power user i need to be aware of the consequences of my actions faving a tweet means maybe stepping on the toes of my followers this is bad for all parties involved i can still use it of course but now it s like a russian roulette fart into someone else s twitter feed i don t want that no one wants that compare this with how facebook like buttons operate behind the scenes and you can see the pattern i avoided liking posts on facebook because i didn t want my feed polluted with suggested junk and now i will avoid faving any posts on twitter to help keep my followers feeds free from junk these are two fascinating examples of how design choices can unintentionally break a feature if i m no longer faving tweets i m sure i m not the only one in fact most of the people who fav my tweets are what i would consider power users it wouldn t surprise me if i stopped receiving favs altogether brian feeney ');
